S1

This electronic supplementary material aims to document in a reproducible manner the simulation results presented in the main text regarding the no-intervention sub-models (SEI3R and SEI3RD).

1 Basic reproduction number (\(\Re_0\))

In this section, we illustrate the procedure to derive an analytical expression for the SEI3R’s basic reproduction number via the next-generation matrix method. This method consists of rewriting the rates of infected states in the form of two matrices. One matrix corresponds to the rate of appearance of new infections (\(V\) matrix), and the other one to the rate of transitions between compartments of infected individuals (\(F\) matrix). The product between \(F\) and \(V^{-1}\) is known as the next-generation matrix, whose largest eigenvalue (spectral radius) corresponds to \(\Re_0\). We obtain the analytical expressions using Mathematica (see R0.nb file in the Github repository).

1.1 \(F\) matrix

F_matrix           <- read_csv("./Data/NI_F_matrix.csv", show_col_types = FALSE)
c_names            <- colnames(F_matrix)
c_names[1]         <- ""
colnames(F_matrix) <- c_names

F_matrix |>
  kbl(escape = FALSE) |> kable_styling(full_width = FALSE)
\(E\) \(P\) \(I\) \(A\)
\(E\) 0 \(\beta\) \(\beta\) \(\eta \beta\)
\(P\) 0 0 0 0
\(I\) 0 0 0 0
\(A\) 0 0 0 0

1.2 \(V\) matrix

F_matrix           <- read_csv("./Data/NI_V_matrix.csv", show_col_types = FALSE)
c_names            <- colnames(F_matrix)
c_names[1]         <- ""
colnames(F_matrix) <- c_names

F_matrix |>
  kbl(escape = FALSE) |> kable_styling(full_width = FALSE)
\(E\) \(P\) \(I\) \(A\)
\(E\) \(\sigma\) 0 0 0
\(P\) \(-(1 - \theta) \omega \sigma\) \(\nu\) 0 0
\(I\) 0 \(-\nu\) \(\gamma\) 0
\(A\) \(-(1 - \omega) \sigma\) 0 0 \(\kappa\)

1.3 Spectral radius

\[\begin{equation} \Re_0 = \beta \left(\omega \left(\frac{1}{\gamma }+\frac{1}{\nu }\right) + \frac{\eta -\eta \omega }{\kappa }\right) \end{equation}\]

2 Simulations

2.1 Attack rate

We perform simulations for two variants of the within-host profile. Unlike the first variant (SEI3R), the second one accounts for disease-induced mortality (SEI3RD).

set.seed(1550)

samples <- runif(997, beta_vals[[1]], beta_vals[[3]])
betas   <- c(samples, beta_vals) |> sort()

c_df <- data.frame(par_beta = betas)
mdl <- read_xmile("./models/1A_SEI3R.stmx", 
                  const_list = bio_params)

fn <- "./saved_objects/1A_sens.rds"

if(!file.exists(fn)) {
  
  # Without mortality (SEI3R)
  wo_mort <- sd_sensitivity_run(mdl$deSolve_components, 
                              consts_df    = c_df,
                              integ_method = "rk4", start_time = 0,
                              stop_time    = 150, 
                              timestep     = 1 / 16,
                              multicore    = TRUE)
  
  SEI3R_df <- wo_mort |> select(time, C, iter, par_beta)
  
  saveRDS(SEI3R_df, fn)
   
} else SEI3R_df <- readRDS(fn)
SEI3R_df <- SEI3R_df |>
  mutate(c     = C / pop_val,
         model = "SEI3R")
mdl2 <- read_xmile("./models/1B_SEI3RD.stmx",
                  const_list = c(bio_params, 
                                 list(par_rho = 0.025)))
fn <- "./saved_objects/1B_sens.rds"

if(!file.exists(fn)) {
  
  # With mortality (SEI3RD)
  mort_df <- sd_sensitivity_run(mdl2$deSolve_components, 
                              consts_df    = c_df,
                              integ_method = "rk4", start_time = 0,
                              stop_time    = 150, 
                              timestep     = 1 / 16,
                              multicore    = TRUE)
  
  SEI3RD_df <- mort_df |> select(time, C, iter, par_beta)
  
  saveRDS(SEI3RD_df, fn)
   
} else SEI3RD_df <- readRDS(fn)
SEI3RD_df <- SEI3RD_df |>
  mutate(c     = C / pop_val,
         model = "SEI3RD")
df <- bind_rows(SEI3R_df, SEI3RD_df)

plot_fig_02(df) -> g

ggsave("./plots/Fig_02_Attack_rate.pdf", plot = g, 
       height = 4, width = 7)

g

2.2 Final size

To further illustrate that incorporating disease-induced mortality does not substantially impact the dynamics of the within-host profile, we compare the attack rates obtained from both variants at day 150.

df2 <- df |> filter(time == 150)

plot_final_size(df2)
